Pattern: Silent centralization
The system presents as distributed while core controls quietly become consolidated.
Observed in: Governance heavy chains, validator governed systems, admin upgrade protocols.
Behavior: A few operators, multisigs, or infrastructure providers become the real control plane.
Risk impl: The protocol’s resilience is overstated because the single points of failure are hidden in plain sight.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Incentive capture spiral
Once one actor learns how to farm the system, others copy the pattern until the whole protocol degrades.
Observed in: Token incentive networks, reputation systems.
Behavior: Honest users either imitate the exploitative behavior or exit.
Risk impl: The protocol rewards the worst adaptation first and then normalizes it.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Governance theater
Governance continues to function as a public ritual after real decision making has already moved elsewhere.
Observed in: DAOs, token holder voting systems, foundation governed ecosystems.
Behavior: Votes happen, but outcomes are shaped by prior coordination, legal control, or off chain influence.
Risk impl: Stakeholders misprice their actual influence and underestimate capture risk.
Frequency: medium

Pattern: Recovery path collapse
When something fails, the protocol has no clean way to restore trust, liquidity, or operating continuity.
Observed in: Cross chain systems, agent execution networks.
Behavior: Incident response becomes ad hoc, slow, and politically contested.
Risk impl: The first failure becomes a confidence event, not just a technical event.
Frequency: medium
